        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>Free Online Image Compressor</h2>
            <p>Our image compression tool helps you reduce the file size of your images while maintaining acceptable visual quality. This is essential for improving website loading speeds, saving storage space, and optimizing images for web use.</p>
            
            <h3>Why Compress Images?</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Faster website loading</strong> - Smaller images load quicker, improving user experience</li>
                <li><strong>Save storage space</strong> - Compressed images take up less disk space</li>
                <li><strong>Reduce bandwidth usage</strong> - Important for mobile users and data limits</li>
                <li><strong>Better SEO performance</strong> - Page speed is a ranking factor for search engines</li>
                <li><strong>Faster email attachments</strong> - Compressed images send more quickly</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>How to Use Our Image Compressor</h3>
            <p>Using our tool is simple: upload your image, adjust the compression settings, preview the result, and download the optimized version. All processing happens directly in your browser - your images are never uploaded to any server, ensuring complete privacy.</p>
            
            <h3>Supported Image Formats</h3>
            <p>Our image compressor works with JPG, JPEG, PNG, and WebP formats. For best results with photographs, use JPG format. For images with transparency, PNG is recommended.</p>
            
            <h3>Tips for Best Compression Results</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Start with quality around 80% - this often provides good balance</li>
                <li>Resize images to the maximum dimensions needed for your use case</li>
                <li>For web use, consider converting PNG to JPG when transparency isn't needed</li>
                <li>Compare the original and compressed versions to ensure quality is acceptable</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        
